<Base title="Lurking, Aesthetic of Withdrawal and Y2K — Michalina Sablik">
  <div class="container page-content">
    <h1>Lurking, Aesthetic of Withdrawal and Y2K. On Laureta Hajrullahu's Practice</h1>
    <p class="exhibition-detail-venue">Curatorial essay | "to undo, to crumble, to vanish" — National Gallery of Kosovo, 2026</p>
    <div class="exhibition-detail-body">
      <p>The essay explores contemporary gaming aesthetics and online culture. It discusses how games devoid of a clearly defined goal, suspended between stasis and wandering, represent shifts in cultural expression, including walking simulators and posthumanist perspectives that allow players to embody non-human entities.</p>
      <p>Central to the text is the concept of the "aesthetics of withdrawal" as deliberate removal from visibility—a political gesture against digital capitalism's demand for constant content production. Object-oriented play and lurking (remaining concealed on social media) function as resistance strategies in an attention economy.</p>
      <p>The installation features two oversized pixelated stone objects with projected holograms. Stones historically marked territorial boundaries; today they metaphorically represent the tension between fixed borders and fluid digital identities. The video work <em>That Which Gave Chase</em> (2026) presents a protagonist trapped in repetitive gameplay, expressing powerlessness within liminal spaces.</p>
      <p>Hajrullahu deliberately conflates aesthetic registers—combining candy-like visuals with brutal content. The artist transforms immaterial game elements into physical obstacles, questioning the conventionality of fixed principles through absurdity.</p>
      <p>The exhibition references Y2K aesthetics and internet culture's slime motif, representing formless, responsive existence. The internet once promised escape; now users seek refuge from surveillance and AI-generated content proliferation.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
